Dark of the Moon has an impressive wing suit sequence, Age of Extinction has the Dinobots (even if they came in way too late) and The Last Knight has Anthony Hopkins. The first film has boring and unfunny Sam Witwicky scenes that are borderline unwatchable mixed with stupid and boring scenes with Rachel Taylor's character and boring army scenes and it just sucks. Anybody who says "oh, the first one was ALRIGHT" are wrong and stupid and that's not just my opinion that's a fact.

Comment: Round 4: mostly ignoring the arguments because I don't think anybody properly fought their point. Age of Extinction is by far the worst Transformers (haven't seen the new one, maybe its worse IDK). That said Phantom Menace is the clear winner and the reason is actually an argument that was made. In a Transformers movie you know exactly what you are going to get and you get it, if you don't like it it's your own fault for buying a ticket. Phantom Menace shits all over everything great about Star Wars. The light saber fight is not the best light saber fight, in fact I might call it the worst. It was nonsensical garbage and Darth Maul was not a bad ass. Maul was trying so hard to be badass and failed so spectacularly. No amount of fight choreography can cover the fact that the fight has no meaning, no weight, it's so pointless that they kill off 2 of the main characters in the film to attempt to force some meaning into it and they still failed. It doesn't hold a candle to literally any other fight in the series. It doesn't have remotely the emotional impact of Vader vs Luke in Jedi. Vader smacking down rebels at the end of Rogue One is a better light saber fight. Even Vader and Obi Wan's half ass fight in A New Hope is better.

Comment: Ok follow me for a bit. The movie opens up with a young boy wearing a tattered set of clothes running through the forest of 1700's maine. He looks lost and scared. He desperately looks around for someone. He is thirsty and tired. He looks and sees a  well. Runs to it in hopes of getting a drink. He looks down and sees a bucket of water. He reaches down and it is just out of reach. Just as he is about to reach it a white gloved hand reaches out of the water and pulls him in. Pennywise takes him to his lair and bites his hand off. The boy screams. Just as he is about to bite the rest of the poor boys arm off he sees that the boys hand grows back. Pennywise looks at the boy in the face and says "Why James what kind of special boy are you?" Thats right the young boy is a young Wolvrine. Pennywise feasts on the ever healing James for days until his brother Sabertooth is able to track him down and save him. The movie then moves forward in time to the present day. The x-men get a report that young mutant children have been disappearing in maine. So they go to investigate and square off against Pennywise.

1)  Man of Steel-  I have only left the theatre angry after watching 3 movies in my life and two of them were in the DCEU franchise and Man of Steel was the first.  Zach Snyder has no concept of what Superman is or should be.  He took a the epitome of optimistic superhero characters and put him in muted, dark, and depressing story that set the tone for how DC Comics would be represented as for at least until Wonder Woman came out (there's even an argument to be made that that movie was too dark.)  It takes Jonathan Kent who is supposed to be the guiding light of morality for Superman, and Snyder makes him give the argument that heroes should let children drown if the outcome may be inconvenient.  Also, Superman who is supposed to stand for hope, not to mention truth and justice, is a murderer who causes the destruction of several 9/11s due to ineptitude.  This is a terrible movie, a terrible depiction of Superman, and it poisoned the well for the DCEU.

2)  Home Alone-  The first two movies are some of the best kids films ever made and then the franchise got progressively worse with each made for tv/direct to dvd addition.  So, let's have Pennywise, an entity that feeds off the fear of children, and have him face off against a kid that overcomes his fears and fights it off with deathtrap after deathtrap.  

3)  Neil Patrick Harris, Harold and Kumar Go to White Castle-  NPH shows up out of nowhere in this film without a hint of foreshadowing and it's the most memorable part of the film.  NPH plays a hilarious version of "himself" that shows off his acting range because this version couldn't be further from the real man.  It's the most memorable part of the film, and it was not only the beginning of a franchise for him, but the comeback that his career needed.  Without this cameo, there would be know Barney Stinson.

4)  Pirates of the Caribbean: On Stranger Tides-  Full disclosure, I love the first 3 Pirates movies.  But, "On Stranger Tides" is terrible.  All of the new characters fell flat, there is far too much Jack Sparrow, and the plot is nonsensical and easily forgotten.  The movie is so bad that none of the new characters or any of the plot of this film is mentioned again in the next film of the franchise.  (My answer would totally have been Transformers: Dark of the Moon if it wasn't already taken.)

5)  Bonnie Wright and Daniel Radcliffe, The Harry Potter films-   The romance between Harry Potter and Ginny Weasley may have been different in the books, but these two had no reason to be together in the films, but more so, the actors looked bored together.

6)  Jack Black-  There's nothing about Jack Black's personality or career that says dark.  You wouldn't be able to take him seriously as the suave Bruce Wayne and certainly couldn't take him seriously as the Batman.  Can you imagine Jack Black in an anatomically correct rubber suit?

7)  Julie Walters as Mrs. Molly Weasley, The Harry Potter series-  She cares deeply for and protects not only her own 7 children but is like a second mother to Harry Potter.  Her children love her and she lives to take care of her family.  And when Bellatrix and the Death Eaters threaten her children, she kills Bellatrix to protect them.  You don't get much better than that.

8)  Ace Ventura-  After Son of the Mask, I don't think you can save that franchise even if Jim Carrey was to return to the role of Stanley Ipkiss.

9)  South Park: Bigger, Longer, and Uncut-  It gave you everything that you could love from South Park and made brought it to the cinematic level.  It works just as much as a satirical comedy about censorship and bigotry as it does as a send up of movie musicals.  It was even nominated for an Academy Award for Best Original Song.  Without South Park: Bigger, Longer, and Uncut there would not be a Book of Mormon.

Comment:
"When you see Endgame in the coming weeks, please don't spoil it for others, the same way you wouldn't want it spoiled for you.  

Remember, Thanos still demands your silence. As always, good luck and happy viewing..." The Russo Brothers


Didn't even feel like a 3 h movie, it was gratifying how the story ended. Even if this story really ends in the upcoming Spidey-film. Is there sadness in the air. Of course there is. Sadness, tears of sorrow, also tears of joy and almost happiness and satisfaction in the end. Sad to see the heroes, that you know and love go, but at the same time satisfied for some of the heroes journey ended. Loki got his last hurrah and Steve's especially got a worthy ending. He did use a lot of language throughout. 


Who knows, what will happen during the next decade inside the franchise, when Disney+ releases the series, which hopefully are properly linked to these movies. No-one, who's worked to make these movies possible probably imagine, just how big the MCU would really get. It's gigantic and cannot be replicated. 


Marvel should do the most epic montage for our heroes. Human or non-human.

Comment: Guys, guys, guys....I've just finished watching Avengers Endgame about 20 mins ago. and Nothing! Absolutely NOTHING will prepare you for a 3 hour Geekfest! We in the Philippines saw the movie 6hours ago and the whole theater I was on was cheering and crying whilst (again) personalities dear to the fans gave their swan song. And lemme tell you, the Net rumors about Steve Rogers saying farewell, well, It's a farewell but on a methaphorical, time- tampered goodbye kind of way, lemme just tell all the fans, Nothing that the Net rumors / plot theories describe what's gonna happen within the last Hour. Absolute Geekfest! The whole theater, young and old, able and disabled, war-torn geek and MCU newbie, everyone jumped, cheered and cried(I mean, massive wailing!) at A certain Hero's funeral service. He was there at the beginning, He was there at the end. and if you think the Captain Marvel movie was women empowerment, fellow geeks, you have no idea what Avengers Endgame is gonna show. The women! The Women! The whole marvel universe women!!! are gonna steal some glory for only a few moments BUT the moment was GLORIOUS!!! Even thor's coming in wakanda in Infinity War never comes close to it! and YES!!!! Captain America Wields a weapon he previously thought himself unworthy to bear(wink, wink!). And the immortal lines "Avengers! Assemble!!" When the good Captain utters it, not a few were having tears of joy. Well, I've spoiled enough folks, I'm gonna watch it again a few hours from now. Lastly, Thanos shows why he is the meanest, most egotistical, and unbelievably convincing Badass in the universe. I ca'nt type here what Cap Marvel does to him, though.... Excelsior! ...oh, Stan Lee has a cameo, it's fast, just watch for it!

Title: Avengers: Endgame Oscar Campaign Begins, But No Robert Downey Jr. - Movie Talk
Comment: Rey having parents or not having parents is irrelevant. She could be a nobody, or she could be from a family that has a history of force users. It doesn't matter, but it would give us, the audience, something interesting, you know like character development, which she really hasn't had yet. The argument that it diminishes what makes her 'special' is stupid. The only reason she is special is because she has the force, not because she's an orphan. Everyone can have the force argument is also way beyond stupid. Since when has George Lucas ever said or written that only specific people can have the force? The only thing he said was that you need midichlorians, and it's these microscopic beings that connect you to the force and allow you to use it. So yeah, anybody could be born with those things inside them. This is not a new concept, despite what some people would have us believe. But even if you have those, you still need serious training so that you can utilize them. How much training has Rey had? About 5 minutes worth and some books, and we're supposed to be rooting for her? This is the same problem I see everywhere. Some people don't want to work for anything, they want it all handed to them on a silver platter. Rey is a prime example, except that it is the writers who are handing her everything on a silver platter. Being strong with the force does not automatically make you a hero, a good person or an interesting character. It's the struggles they go through and the way they learn from their mistakes and grow as a person that makes us root for them. But Rey has had no struggle to get what she wants (other than scavenging on Jakku), not to mention that we still don't really know what she actually wants, other than her family. We know so little about her, so yeah, why not delve into who her parents were.

Title: Watch LIVE : Landing of Chandrayaan-2 on Moon&#39
Comment:
Actually, it deviated at an altitude of 4km. From that (38:28) onwards the progress was not as intended.

At 39:18 central engine should have been started, but I think it didn't (or exploded?). So a sharp decrease in altitude.

Remember it still had a high vertical velocity, so the impact speed is more than what it would have been for free fall before touching the surface. It would be a catastrophic damage to the instruments inside.

At 1:11:30, one can hear in the background a women scientist saying there is a lot of change in the doppler data.

Lander technology is new to ISRO, seperating with orbiter in the space, doing those complex maneuvers, following the intended path until 2.1 km is exceptionally good. That too all these things were done by the lander itself, no commands from the control i.e, automated.

If it lands in one piece on it's four legs, in right orientation to get max sunlight, then it's miracle. In that scenario one can hope for less damage to the instruments and to the rover. Hope for the best üáÆüá≥.

Title: Chandrayaan 2 - Landing on Moon - LIVE from MOX-ISTRAC, Peenya, Bengaluru
Comment: From the trajectory graph, it seems there should be some problem with some trajectory autocorrection module in the lander. Why do I think so? If you look closely at the red curve and at the blue curve, you will see a small spike the green curve makes towards north and is almost immediately brought back to the intended curve (red) by "something" (I think this "something" is some autocorrection module). Now the spike upwards or away from the red curve is caused by "something" on the moon's surface which we dont know (moon has very little atmosphere, so can't be wind, I guess.) . But the lander immediately autocorrects its path and is back on the red line. Next time that same factor hits the lander again. And this time for elongated duration of time. Why the elongated duration of time? I dont think it is because of the factor deviating the lander. I think it is a burst shot and not some continuous force. I think the trajectory autocorrection module did not start immediately this time. So the duration of time the lander was out of the red line was significantly more than the first time. Now it is commonsense to assume that once the autocorrection module starts, the lander is trying to regain its intended trajectory(the red curve) "more aggressively" than the first time. And so now you can see the lander going in the southern direction (in respect to the red curve). Maybe that module was not written correctly. So it did not stop at the right time (neither did it start at the right time). The influence of that module continued even though the effect was not present anymore. As a result it drifted more and more away from the red curve, finally crashing into the surface
